  <section class="mb-faq-section" id="faqs">
    <div class="mb-container">
      <div class="mb-section-header">
        <h2 class="mb-section-title">MacBook Repair FAQs</h2>
        <p class="mb-section-subtitle">Common questions about MacBook repair at Mobile Tech Lab in Winnipeg</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mb-faq-list">
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>How long does MacBook screen replacement take in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Most MacBook screen replacements are completed within 1–3 business days at our Winnipeg location depending on parts availability for your specific model and year. M3 MacBook Pro Liquid Retina XDR screens may take longer to source — contact us to confirm availability before visiting.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Can you recover data from a water-damaged MacBook in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — in many cases we can recover data from liquid-damaged MacBooks using component-level diagnostics and specialised data recovery tools. Apple Silicon MacBooks store data on chips soldered to the logic board, which makes recovery more complex but still possible in many cases — bring it in as soon as possible for the best outcome.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Do you repair MacBooks with Apple Silicon M1, M2, and M3?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — we repair the full Apple Silicon MacBook lineup including M1, M2, and M3 Air and Pro models. Apple Silicon repairs require different techniques than Intel models due to the tighter integration of logic board, battery, and storage components — our Winnipeg technicians are trained on all generations.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>How much does MacBook battery replacement cost in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">MacBook battery replacement costs vary by model and generation — older Intel models are generally less expensive than M-chip models due to differences in battery integration. Contact us or use our online quote tool for a free upfront price on your specific MacBook model.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Is my data safe during MacBook repair at Mobile Tech Lab?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — your files remain untouched during all hardware repairs. For liquid damage or data recovery cases, we document the device state on arrival and walk you through the process step by step. We recommend backing up your data before any repair when possible.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Can you fix a MacBook with a swollen battery in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — swollen MacBook batteries are a safety issue we treat as urgent. A swollen battery can warp the trackpad and chassis if left unaddressed. We replace swollen batteries on all MacBook models and dispose of the old battery safely. Do not leave a swollen battery unattended — bring it in as soon as possible.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Do you repair MacBook keyboard issues including butterfly keyboard?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — we replace keyboards on all MacBook models including the notorious butterfly mechanism on 2016–2019 MacBook Pros. We replace the full keyboard assembly rather than individual keys for a lasting fix. Most keyboard replacements are completed within 1–2 business days.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Can you fix a MacBook that won't turn on in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — a MacBook that won't power on is often caused by a depleted or failed battery, a liquid-damaged logic board, or a firmware issue. We run free diagnostics to identify the root cause before recommending any repair so you know exactly what the problem is before spending anything.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Do you repair MacBook charging issues in Winnipeg?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — we diagnose and repair all MacBook charging problems including MagSafe connector damage, USB-C port repairs, charging IC faults, and battery connector issues. We test the full charging chain before replacing any parts to avoid unnecessary repairs.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="mb-faq-item">
          <summary class="mb-faq-summary">
            <span>Do you repair MacBooks in Thompson, MB?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="mb-faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <p class="mb-faq-answer">Yes — our Thompson location at 300 Mystery Lake Rd #1530 accepts MacBook repairs Monday through Saturday 10AM–6PM. For screen replacements or less common models, calling ahead helps us confirm parts availability before your visit.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

